# Function to get top N words from the title

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer


def get_top_n_words(corpus, n=None,stopword=None,nrange=(1,1)):
    vec = CountVectorizer(stop_words=stopword,ngram_range=nrange).fit(corpus)
    bag_of_words = vec.transform(corpus)
    sum_words = bag_of_words.sum(axis=0) 
    words_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, idx]) for word, idx in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    words_freq =sorted(words_freq, key = lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    return words_freq[:n]

# Top 20 most common unigrams occuring in all the titles

common_words_withStopwords = get_top_n_words(df_votes['title'], 20)
common_words_withoutStopwords = get_top_n_words(df_votes['title'], 20,'english')

df1 = pd.DataFrame(common_words_withStopwords, columns = ['titleText' , 'count'])
df2 = pd.DataFrame(common_words_withoutStopwords, columns = ['titleText' , 'count'])

f, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(16, 6))
sns.set_color_codes("pastel")
g = sns.barplot(x="titleText", y="count", data=df1, color="b",ax=ax[0])
t = sns.barplot(x="titleText", y="count", data=df2, color="b",ax=ax[1])
g.set_xticklabels(rotation=90,labels=df1['titleText'],fontsize =14)
t.set_xticklabels(rotation=90,labels=df2['titleText'],fontsize =14)
sns.despine(left = True)
plt.suptitle("Top 20 unigram in titles before and after removing stop words",fontsize=16);

Bigrams are most suitable for topic modeling to generate the topics which summarize the titles better.
The Number of topics have been tested for 20 and 30 but both of them have some discrepancies which would be solved by domain knowledge about the articles. Consulting with domain experts in the field to get a clear idea about how many number of topics to be used for topic modeling would increase the efficiency. Some common stop words for articles can also be used to avoid getting words which are not important based on domain knowledge.
Gensim for Topic Modeling has some advanced features which were not tried along with using SpaCy library instead of NLTK could result in better results.

Machine Learning Models¶

Predicting up_votes as a whole number is a Regression problem with more than 1000 values. Also, as more than 75% of up_votes are less than 100, this problem can be converted to binary classification problem with titles having more than 100 up_votes considered as 1 target category whereas all the other titles with < 100 votes as another category.

In [52]:
# Converting up_votes to binary for making it classification problem 

df_votes['rating'] = [1 if i > 100 else 0 for i in df_votes['up_votes']]
In [53]:
# Splitting the data into train and test with 80:20 ratio

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_votes['title'].values, df_votes['rating'].values, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape, X_test.shape, y_test.shape)

# Most informative features for a class
def show_most_and_least_informative_features(vectorizer, clf, class_idx=0, n=10):
    feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names()
    coefs_with_fns = sorted(zip(clf.coef_[class_idx], feature_names))
    top = zip(coefs_with_fns[:n], coefs_with_fns[-n:])
    for (coef_1, fn_1), (coef_2, fn_2) in top:
        print("\t%.4f\t%-15s\t\t%.4f\t%-15s" % (coef_1, fn_1, coef_2, fn_2))

Count Vectorizer gives better result for up_votes = 1 ( 1 for votes > 100) as compared to TFIDF Vectorizer.
The data is highly skewed and there are only a handful of samples for votes =1 which why the MNB is not able to predict this class properly.
Numbers are always catchy when they are part of article titles but the ML models seem to be not benefitting from these. Taking out numbers from the titles can improve the model prediction.
